[2] Russia (Yamal)
Date: Tue 19 Nov 2013
Source: Interfax-Russia [In Russian, trans. & edited. - Mod.CP]
http://www.interfax-russia.ru/Ural/news.asp?id=451940&sec=1672


Measles outbreak recorded in Yamal for the 1st time in 20 years
---------------------------------------------------------------
The Interfax-Ural News Agency has reported that an outbreak of measles virus infection has occurred in the city of Gubkin (Yamal-Nenets Autonomous District), according to the Yamal Epidemiology Service. The Yamal Epidemiology Service announced that a family of unvaccinated individuals had arrived in the city from Dagestan and, according to a preliminary investigation, are thought to be the source of the outbreak.

So far 15 cases of measles, including both children and adults, have been diagnosed with the disease. It is considered likely that additional cases will be diagnosed in the immediate future.

The Yamal Epidemiology Service stated that there had been no measles cases in the district since 1990.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The Yamal Peninsula, located in the Yamal-Nenets autonomous district of north west Siberia, extends roughly 700 km (435 miles) and is bordered principally by the Kara Sea, Baydaratskaya Bay on the west, and by the Gulf of Ob on the east. In the language of its indigenous inhabitants, the Nenets, "Yamal" means "End of the World". Yamal holds Russia's biggest natural gas reserves. The Yurkharovskoye gas field is planned to be developed by the Russian gas monopolist Gazpromby in 2011-2012. A map showing the location of the Yamal Autonomous Okrug can be accessed at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yamalo-Nenets_Autonomous_Okrug. - Mod.CP]

******
[3] Russia (Yamal)
Date: Thu 21 Nov 2013
Source: Vesti-yamal.ru News Agency [In Russian, trans. & edited. - Mod.CP]
http://vesti-yamal.ru/ru/vjesti_jamal/hvor_pod_nazvanijem_kor_gubkinskij_zaboljel71361#t20c


Measles has broken out in the city of Gubkinsky [Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous District]. The disease was diagnosed in 17 patients who sought treatment for fever and the characteristic rash. The diagnoses were confirmed by the Novosibirsk Diagnostic Center. The majority of the confirmed cases are children. The infection occurred in preschool children attending 2 day-care centers. The situation was discussed at a special meeting of the city's Anti-Epidemic Commission.

Four of the cases were registered in a neighbouring community. Measles is an airborne infection. On occasion there have been several hundred patients under treatment in the Gubkinsky hospital. The staff and children attending 2 kindergartens run by the city hospital have been vaccinated already. On Friday [22 Nov 2013], it is planned to administer a further 500 does of vaccine. Overall the level of immunization against measles in Gubkinsky is satisfactory and approaching 97 per cent. A meeting has been convened to discuss additional purchases of vaccine and the possibility of increasing the number of beds in the hospital isolation ward, and to install improved containment facilities.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Gubkinsky is a town in the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug located on the left bank of the Pyakupur River, south of Salekhard. Population: 23 335 (2010 Census). A map showing the location of Gubkinsky can be accessed at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gubkinsky_(town).

Despite the high level of vaccination against measles in Russsia, cases are now appearing in the colder northern regions of the country. - Mod.CP]

******
[4] UK (England)
Date: Fri 22 Nov 2013
Source: Public Health England, Health Protection Report 2013; 7(47) [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.hpa.org.uk/hpr/infections/immunisation.htm#mmrq3


Laboratory confirmed cases of measles (England): Jul to Sep 2013
----------------------------------------------------------------
Data presented here are for the 3rd quarter of 2013 (July to September). Cases include those confirmed by oral fluid testing (IgM antibody tests and/or PCR) at the Virus Reference Department, Colindale, and national routine laboratory reports. Analyses are by date of onset. Regional breakdown figures relate to Government Office Regions rather than regional health authorities.

Only 103 cases of measles were confirmed in England with onset dates in the 3rd quarter of 2013 compared with 609 cases in the previous quarter. As previously reported, the region with the highest number of cases this quarter was South West (45 cases), although cases were confirmed in most regions of England. An additional 4 infections were confirmed by oral fluid testing of cases from Wales.

The majority (71/103, 69 per cent) of the English measles cases this quarter were in children and adolescents: 5 (5 per cent) under one year; 20 (19 per cent) aged 1 to 4 years; 18 (17 per cent) aged 5 to 9 year, 17 (17 per cent) aged 10 to 14 years; 11 (11 per cent) aged 15 to 18 years. The remaining 32 cases (31 per cent) were adults aged 19 to 56 years. Seven per cent (7/103 cases) of cases reported receiving 1 (4 cases) or 2 (3 cases) doses of a measles-containing vaccine.

Three cases reported a history of recent travel; one each to Pakistan and China, and one further case believed to have acquired measles through travel, possibly linked to contact within airports rather than any particular country visited.

Within the European Union and European Economic Area (EU/EEA), 2 countries are experiencing large measles outbreaks; the Dutch authorities have reported 1540 measles cases since May 2013, although the actual number of cases is estimated to be much higher, and in Germany the number of reported measles cases this year [2013] is nearly 10 times higher than the total cases in 2012. In the year up to July 2013, only 11/30 EU/EEA countries have met the elimination target of less than one case of measles per million of population, and in the EU neighbouring countries, measles outbreaks are on-going in the Russian federation, Turkey and Georgia.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is disappointing to learn that only 11 of 30 European countries have met the elimination target of less than one case of measles per million of population, and in neighbouring non-EU countries, measles outbreaks are on-going in the Russian federation, Turkey and Georgia.

A ProMED-mail HealthMap of England can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1fj0. - Mod.CP]

