[5] Canada (Alberta)
Date: Mon 18 Nov 2013
Source: 660News [edited]
http://www.660news.com/2013/11/18/confirmed-measles-cases-in-southern-alberta-reach-32/


Confirmed measles cases in southern Alberta reach 32
----------------------------------------------------
Parents are being urged to review their children's immunization records, as more and more children are diagnosed with the unwelcome red dots. The medical officer of health for Alberta Health Services [AHS] in the Calgary area tells 660News, not one case of measles has been reported here since the outbreak began a month ago [October 2013]. Still, Dr Judy Macdonald is urging moms and dads to check on their children's vaccination records to make sure they did receive 2 doses of the vaccine before they started school. People who were born in 1970 or later are also urged to make sure they have been properly immunized.

Macdonald says according to government records it appears about 90 per cent of the population has been properly inoculated, which still leaves about 10 per cent not protected. And with winter fast approaching, AHS is also reminding people to take advantage of flu vaccination clinics, which are operating across the province.

[byline: Kevin Usselman]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In ProMED-mail Measles update (46), part 5, it was reported that: "As of Wednesday morning [14 Nov 2013], there are 28 cases of measles confirmed in the province, and Alberta Health Services (AHS) is turning its attention to 2 new communities in hopes of containing the outbreak. Vaccination clinics have been set up in 2 Hills and Lacombe for children aged 6 months to 17 years old and for those aged 4-17 who have not had a 2nd dose of the measles vaccine.

"The chief medical officer of AHS told Global News that the outbreak is expected to spread from the South Zone communities of Coaldale and Fort Macleod to other low immunization communities. 'We know that in the south, there are a number of communities that have ties -- and they're low immunisation rates -- and they have ties with other areas of the province,' explained Dr Martin Lavoie. 'Depending on how low those rates are, how close the ties are, we're expecting a spread from the south. It's just a matter of time to spread from there to those other low immunization communities.'"

Curiously, the above press report announces that the number of measles cases in South Alberta has risen to 32, and simultaneously announces that: "The medical officer of health for Alberta Health Services in the Calgary area tells 660News, that not one case of measles has been reported here since the outbreak began a month ago." Clarification of the situation would be appreciated.

A ProMED-mail HealthMap can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/73a6. - Mod.CP]
